            {
              "id": "0ed5fd0d-2c74-3c4c-b277-189b95162db1",
              "name": "\"POST Route Lacks CSRF Protection Vulnerability\"",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe \"POST Route Lacks CSRF Protection Vulnerability\" is a security flaw in a web application where the POST route does not have Cross-Site Request Forgery (CSRF) protection. CSRF is an attack that tricks the victim into submitting a malicious request. It uses the identity and privileges of the victim to perform an undesired function on their behalf.\n\nIn the given code snippet, the POST route '/modifyproduct' lacks CSRF protection. This means that if an attacker can trick a user into clicking a link or loading a page, the attacker can modify product details on behalf of the user without their consent.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, you should implement CSRF tokens in your POST routes. CSRF tokens are random values associated with a user's session, which are expected to be sent with every state-changing operation (like modifying a product). This ensures that the server only processes requests where the token matches the one associated with the user's session, preventing CSRF attacks.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere's how you can modify the given code to include CSRF protection using the `csurf` middleware:\n\n```javascript\nvar csrf = require('csurf');\nvar csrfProtection = csrf({ cookie: true });\n\nrouter.post('/modifyproduct', authHandler.isAuthenticated, csrfProtection, appHandler.modifyProductSubmit);\n```\n\nIn this code, `csrfProtection` is a middleware that validates the CSRF token sent in the request. If the token is missing or invalid, it will throw an error.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following library dependencies:\n\n- Express: A web application framework for Node.js.\n- csurf: CSRF protection middleware for Express.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP CSRF Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Cross-Site_Request_Forgery_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-352: Cross-Site Request Forgery (CSRF)](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/352.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-352",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/352.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-352"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "158c36a9-9607-3953-94bc-53ddffe1b780",
              "name": "Missing Authorization Check in Admin Route",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\n\"Missing Authorization Check in Admin Route\" is a security vulnerability that occurs when an application does not properly protect sensitive functionality. This can allow an attacker to gain unauthorized access to privileged functions. In the context of JavaScript and Node.js applications, this often occurs when middleware used for authorization checks is not properly implemented or is missing entirely.\n\nIn the provided code snippet, the route `/admin/usersapi` is protected by the `authHandler.isAuthenticated` middleware. This middleware presumably checks if a user is authenticated. However, being authenticated does not necessarily mean the user has the necessary privileges to access this route. If the application does not check if the authenticated user has admin privileges, any authenticated user can access this route.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, you should implement an authorization check that verifies the user has the necessary privileges to access the route. This can be done by adding another middleware that checks the user's role after the authentication check.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is a simple example of how you can implement an authorization check:\n\n```javascript\n// Authorization middleware\nfunction isAdmin(req, res, next) {\n  if (req.user && req.user.role === 'admin') {\n    next();\n  } else {\n    res.status(403).send('Unauthorized');\n  }\n}\n\n// Route with authorization check\nrouter.get('/admin/usersapi', authHandler.isAuthenticated, isAdmin, appHandler.listUsersAPI);\n```\n\nIn this example, the `isAdmin` middleware checks if the authenticated user has the 'admin' role. If they do, the request is passed to the next middleware or route handler. If they do not, the middleware sends a 403 Unauthorized response.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe provided code snippet appears to be using Express.js and some custom middleware. The required dependencies are:\n\n- express\n- A library or custom code for handling authentication (represented by `authHandler.isAuthenticated` in the code snippet)\n- A library or custom code for handling the application logic (represented by `appHandler.listUsersAPI` in the code snippet)\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Top 10-2017 A5-Broken Access Control](https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/2017/A5_2017-Broken_Access_Control)\n- [CWE-285: Improper Authorization](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/285.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-285",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/285.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-285"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "194ddd46-e637-3aac-9bd6-f279545ed3bf",
              "name": "Unhandled Promise Rejection Vulnerability",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\n\"Unhandled Promise Rejection Vulnerability\" in JavaScript occurs when a Promise is rejected, but this rejection is not caught or handled with a `.catch()` method. This can lead to unexpected application behavior, including crashes, and can potentially expose sensitive information in error messages.\n\nIn the provided code, the vulnerability lies in the `.catch()` block. The error `err` is caught, but nothing is done with it. This means that if the Promise is rejected, the error will not be handled properly.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, you should always handle Promise rejections. This can be done by adding a `.catch()` block to your Promise chain, and then handling the error appropriately within this block. This might involve logging the error, returning a default value, or throwing an error to be caught higher up in your application.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is a fixed version of the provided code:\n\n```javascript\ndb.sequelize.query(query, {\n\tmodel: db.User\n}).then(user => {\n\tif (user.length) {\n\t\tvar output = {\n\t\t\tuser: {\n\t\t\t\tname: user[0].name,\n\t\t\t\tid: user[0].id\n\t\t\t}\n\t\t}\n\t\tres.render('app/usersearch', {\n\t\t\toutput: output\n\t\t})\n\t} else {\n\t\treq.flash('warning', 'User not found')\n\t\tres.render('app/usersearch', {\n\t\t\toutput: null\n\t\t})\n\t}\n}).catch(err => {\n\tconsole.error(err);\n\treq.flash('error', 'An error occurred while searching for the user');\n\tres.render('app/usersearch', {\n\t\toutput: null\n\t});\n});\n```\n\nIn this fixed version, the `.catch()` block logs the error and then flashes a generic error message to the user. It also renders the `usersearch` view with no output.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe provided code requires the following library dependencies:\n\n- Sequelize (for the `db.sequelize.query()` method)\n- Express (for the `res.render()` method)\n- Connect-flash (for the `req.flash()` method)\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Unhandled Promise Rejection](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Nodejs_Security_Cheat_Sheet.html#unhandled-promise-rejections)\n- [CWE-754: Improper Check for Unusual or Exceptional Conditions](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/754.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-755",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/755.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-755"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "19d2a2dc-74e6-3047-98f6-987c4094ba29",
              "name": "Unhandled Promise Rejection Vulnerability",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nUnhandled Promise Rejection Vulnerability in JavaScript occurs when a promise is rejected, but there is no error handling mechanism in place to catch and handle the error. This can lead to unexpected application behavior, including crashes, and can potentially expose sensitive information in error messages.\n\nIn the provided code, the promise returned by `db.Product.findAll()` is not being caught for errors. If the promise is rejected (for example, if there is a problem connecting to the database), the error will not be handled and the application may crash.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, you should always include error handling when working with promises. This can be done using `.catch()` or by using `try/catch` with async/await.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is a fixed version of the code:\n\n```javascript\ndb.Product.findAll({\n\twhere: {\n\t\tname: {\n\t\t\t[Op.like]: '%' + req.body.name + '%'\n\t\t}\n\t}\n}).then(products => {\n\toutput = {\n\t\tproducts: products,\n\t\tsearchTerm: req.body.name\n\t}\n\tres.render('app/products', {\n\t\toutput: output\n\t})\n}).catch(err => {\n\t// Handle the error here\n\tconsole.error(err);\n\tres.status(500).send('An error occurred');\n});\n```\n\nIn this version, if the promise is rejected, the error will be caught and logged, and a 500 response will be sent.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following library dependencies:\n\n- Sequelize (for `db.Product.findAll()`)\n- Express (for `req`, `res`, and `res.render()`)\n- An Express-compatible view engine (for `res.render()`)\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Unhandled Promise Rejection](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Nodejs_Security_Cheat_Sheet.html#unhandled-promise-rejections)\n- [CWE-754: Improper Check for Unusual or Exceptional Conditions](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/754.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-755",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/755.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-755"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "1b1b1c48-c47c-359a-9cdc-094d5ac6f7db",
              "name": "Unselected Field Database Query Vulnerability",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\n\"Unselected Field Database Query Vulnerability\" in JavaScript is a security flaw that occurs when a developer does not explicitly define the fields to be returned from a database query. This can lead to the exposure of sensitive data. In the provided code, the query is fetching a product by its 'id' from the database, but it does not specify which fields of the product should be returned. This means that all fields of the product, including potentially sensitive ones, will be returned.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, developers should always explicitly define the fields to be returned from a database query. This can be done by adding a 'select' clause to the query, which specifies the fields to be returned. If a field is not specified in the 'select' clause, it will not be returned by the query.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is a fixed version of the provided code:\n\n```javascript\ndb.Product.find({\n    where: {\n        'id': req.query.id\n    },\n    attributes: ['id', 'name', 'description'] // specify the fields to be returned\n}).then(product => {\n    // ...\n});\n```\n\nIn this fixed version, the 'attributes' option is used to specify the fields to be returned by the query. Only the 'id', 'name', and 'description' fields of the product will be returned.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe provided code appears to be using the Sequelize ORM for Node.js. Therefore, the following library dependencies are required:\n\n- `sequelize`: This is the main Sequelize library.\n- `pg` or `mysql`: These are the database drivers. You should install the one that matches your database system.\n- `express`: This is used to handle HTTP requests and responses.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP - SQL Injection Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/SQL_Injection_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-209: Information Exposure Through an Error Message](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/209.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-200",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/200.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-200"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "1e96d829-722c-3dc8-892a-0bc1415eb610",
              "name": "\"Remote Code Execution Vulnerability via Object Deserialization in serialize.unserialize Function\"",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe \"Remote Code Execution Vulnerability via Object Deserialization in serialize.unserialize Function\" is a critical security vulnerability in JavaScript programming language. It occurs when an application deserializes untrusted data without proper validation, which can lead to arbitrary code execution. In this case, the vulnerability is in the `serialize.unserialize` function.\n\nThe `serialize.unserialize` function is used to convert a serialized string back into a JavaScript object. If an attacker can control the input to this function, they can craft a serialized string that, when deserialized, leads to arbitrary code execution.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, you should avoid deserializing data from untrusted sources. If this is not possible, you should use a safe, standard data format such as JSON, and use the built-in functions `JSON.parse` and `JSON.stringify` to serialize and deserialize data.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nReplace the `serialize.unserialize` function with `JSON.parse`:\n\n```javascript\nvar products = JSON.parse(req.files.products.data.toString('utf8'));\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following library dependencies:\n\n- `express` for handling HTTP requests.\n- `multer` for handling `multipart/form-data`, which is primarily used for uploading files.\n\n## OWASP Resources\n\n- [OWASP Top 10 2017: A8-Insecure Deserialization](https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/2017/A8_2017-Insecure_Deserialization)\n- [OWASP Cheat Sheet: Deserialization Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Deserialization_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n\n## Common Weakness Enumeration (CWE)\n\n- [CWE-502: Deserialization of Untrusted Data](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/502.html)\n\nPlease note that all the links provided are active and accessible to anonymous users."
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-502",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/502.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-502"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "1fae96e7-4e84-34c7-bfea-ce5a023516f1",
              "name": "Unprotected SQL Logging in Sequelize Initialization",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nUnprotected SQL Logging in Sequelize Initialization is a vulnerability that occurs when the Sequelize ORM (Object-Relational Mapping) for Node.js is initialized without properly protecting the SQL logging function. This can potentially expose sensitive information such as SQL queries, database structure, and other data that should be kept confidential. This vulnerability can lead to SQL Injection attacks, data breaches, and other security issues.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, it is recommended to disable SQL logging in production environments or at least ensure that the logs do not contain sensitive information. This can be done by using a custom logging function that filters out sensitive data.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is a simple fix for the vulnerability:\n\n```javascript\nvar sequelize = new Sequelize(process.env.DATABASE_URL, {\n  logging: process.env.NODE_ENV === 'production' ? false : console.log\n});\n```\n\nIn this code, SQL logging is disabled in a production environment by setting the `logging` option to `false`. In a non-production environment, `console.log` is used for logging.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following library dependencies:\n\n- `sequelize`: This is the Sequelize library, a promise-based Node.js ORM for Postgres, MySQL, MariaDB, SQLite, and Microsoft SQL Server.\n- `dotenv`: This is a zero-dependency module that loads environment variables from a `.env` file into `process.env`.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP SQL Injection Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/SQL_Injection_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-89: Improper Neutralization of Special Elements used in an SQL Command ('SQL Injection')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/89.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-532",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/532.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-532"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "2210a9d6-f3a3-3d11-9eaa-757cf47b15cd",
              "name": "Unhandled Promise Rejection Vulnerability",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\n\"Unhandled Promise Rejection Vulnerability\" in JavaScript occurs when a Promise is rejected, but there is no error handling mechanism in place to catch and handle the error. This can lead to unexpected application behavior, crashes, and potential security vulnerabilities. In the provided code, the Promise returned by `db.User.findAll({})` is not being handled for a case where it might get rejected.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, always handle Promise rejections by providing a `.catch()` block or by using `try/catch` with async/await. This allows you to handle any errors that occur during the execution of the Promise and prevent unexpected application behavior.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is how you can fix the provided code:\n\n```javascript\ndb.User.findAll({})\n  .then(users => {\n    res.status(200).json({\n      success: true,\n      users: users\n    });\n  })\n  .catch(err => {\n    console.error(err);\n    res.status(500).json({\n      success: false,\n      message: 'An error occurred while fetching users'\n    });\n  });\n```\n\nIn this fixed code, if the Promise returned by `db.User.findAll({})` is rejected, the `.catch()` block will handle the error, preventing the Unhandled Promise Rejection.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe provided code seems to be using the following libraries:\n\n- Sequelize (for `db.User.findAll({})`)\n- Express (for `res.status().json()`)\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Unhandled Promise Rejection](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Nodejs_Security_Cheat_Sheet.html#unhandled-promise-rejections)\n- [CWE-754: Improper Check for Unusual or Exceptional Conditions](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/754.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-755",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/755.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-755"
                ]
              }
            },
