            {
              "id": "283c37fd-24cf-3a12-b3bf-9afd87be6631",
              "name": "Non-literal $EXEC() calls detected, potential for command injection vulnerability.",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe vulnerability \"Non-literal $EXEC() calls detected, potential for command injection vulnerability\" refers to a situation where a function that executes system commands (in this case, `exec()`) is called with a string that is constructed using user input (`req.body.address`). This can lead to a command injection vulnerability if the user input is not properly sanitized, as an attacker could provide a string that, when executed as a command, could harm the system.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, you should avoid using user input directly in system commands. If it is necessary to use user input in system commands, the input should be properly sanitized to ensure that it does not contain any malicious commands. \n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is a fixed version of the code using the `child_process.execFile()` function, which is safer because it does not use the shell to execute the command:\n\n```javascript\nvar execFile = require('child_process').execFile;\n\nexecFile('ping', ['-c', '2', req.body.address], function (err, stdout, stderr) {\n    output = stdout + stderr;\n    res.render('app/ping', {\n        output: output\n    });\n});\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following library dependencies:\n\n- `child_process`: This is a built-in Node.js module and does not need to be installed separately.\n- `express`: This is used to handle HTTP requests and responses. It can be installed with `npm install express`.\n- Some template engine (like `ejs`, `pug`, etc.) to render the response. It can be installed with `npm install ejs` or `npm install pug`.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Command Injection](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/Command_Injection)\n- [CWE-78: Improper Neutralization of Special Elements used in an OS Command ('OS Command Injection')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/78.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-78",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/78.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-78"
                ]
              }
