            {
              "id": "503041b8-7c2c-3470-86ff-ec0070f4844b",
              "name": "\"POST Route Lacks CSRF Protection Vulnerability\"",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe \"POST Route Lacks CSRF Protection Vulnerability\" is a security flaw in a web application where the POST route does not have Cross-Site Request Forgery (CSRF) protection. CSRF is an attack that tricks the victim into submitting a malicious request. It uses the identity and privileges of the victim to perform an undesired function on their behalf.\n\nIn the given code snippet, the POST route '/bulkproductslegacy' does not have any CSRF protection. This means that if an attacker can trick a user into clicking a link or loading a page, the attacker can make requests to this route with the user's credentials.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, you should implement CSRF tokens in your POST routes. A CSRF token is a random value associated with a user's session, which is expected to be sent with every state-changing operation (like a POST request). \n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is a simple example of how you can add CSRF protection to your route using the `csurf` middleware in Express.js:\n\n```javascript\nvar csurf = require('csurf');\nvar csrfProtection = csurf({ cookie: true });\n\nrouter.post('/bulkproductslegacy', csrfProtection, authHandler.isAuthenticated, appHandler.bulkProductsLegacy);\n```\n\nIn this code, `csrfProtection` is a middleware that validates the CSRF token. If the token is missing or incorrect, it will throw an error.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following libraries:\n\n- Express.js: A web application framework for Node.js.\n- csurf: CSRF protection middleware for Express.js.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP CSRF Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Cross-Site_Request_Forgery_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-352: Cross-Site Request Forgery (CSRF)](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/352.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-352",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/352.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-352"
                ]
              }
            },
