            {
              "id": "6afaab93-ad55-39a5-a7d4-66581a06b018",
              "name": "Unfiltered Database Query Vulnerability",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nUnfiltered Database Query Vulnerability, also known as NoSQL Injection, is a type of vulnerability where an attacker can inject code into the query that is being run on the database. This can lead to unauthorized access to sensitive data, data loss, or even data corruption. In the provided JavaScript code, the vulnerability lies in the fact that the 'login' field from the request body is directly used in the database query without any sanitization or validation.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, it is recommended to always validate and sanitize user inputs before using them in a database query. This can be done using various input validation libraries available for JavaScript. Also, use parameterized queries or prepared statements to ensure that user inputs are treated as literal values and not executable code.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is a fixed version of the provided code:\n\n```javascript\nconst Sequelize = require('sequelize');\nconst Op = Sequelize.Op;\n\ndb.User.find({\n    where: {\n        'login': {\n            [Op.eq]: req.body.login\n        }\n    }\n}).then(user => {\n    // ...\n});\n```\n\nIn this fixed code, Sequelize, an Object-Relational Mapping (ORM) library for Node.js, is used to create a parameterized query. The `Op.eq` operator is used to ensure that the 'login' field is compared for equality with the user input, preventing any possibility of code injection.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe provided code requires the following library dependencies:\n\n- Express.js (for handling HTTP requests)\n- Sequelize (for interacting with the database)\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Node.js Injection Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Nodejs_Security_Cheat_Sheet.html#mongodb-injection)\n- [CWE-89: Improper Neutralization of Special Elements used in an SQL Command ('SQL Injection')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/89.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-200",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/200.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-200"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "7082f437-1ad8-30fc-83a2-a04da48bd609",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "Vulnerability: CVE-2026-24842\\nComponent: CVE-2026-24842/pkg:npm/tar@2.2.2"
