            {
              "id": "7edc0b19-6cd6-3a9d-a61b-f2e6b4ccd34e",
              "name": "SQL Injection Risk from Untrusted Input and Raw SQL Query Concatenation",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe code snippet provided is vulnerable to SQL Injection attacks. This is due to the use of raw SQL query concatenation with untrusted input (`req.body.login`). An attacker can manipulate the `login` parameter to alter the SQL query, potentially gaining unauthorized access to data or performing other malicious activities.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this risk, avoid using raw SQL queries with untrusted input. Instead, use parameterized queries or prepared statements, which can ensure that user input is always treated as literal data, not part of the SQL command.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is a recommended fix using Sequelize's built-in protection against SQL Injection:\n\n```javascript\nvar login = req.body.login;\ndb.User.findOne({\n    where: {\n        login: login\n    }\n}).then(user => {\n    if (user) {\n        var output = {\n            user: {\n                name: user.name,\n                id: user.id\n            }\n        }\n        res.render('app/usersearch', {\n            output: output\n        })\n    } else {\n        req.flash('warning', 'User not found')\n        res.render('app/usersearch', {\n            output: null\n        })\n    }\n}).catch(err => {\n    req.flash('danger', 'Internal Error')\n    res.render('app/usersearch', {\n        output: null\n    })\n})\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following library dependencies:\n\n- Sequelize: A promise-based Node.js ORM for Postgres, MySQL, MariaDB, SQLite and Microsoft SQL Server.\n- Express.js: A web application framework for Node.js, used for routing HTTP requests.\n- Connect-flash: A middleware for Express.js to handle flash messages.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP SQL Injection Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/SQL_Injection_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-89: Improper Neutralization of Special Elements used in an SQL Command ('SQL Injection')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/89.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-89",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/89.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-89"
                ]
              }
            },
