            {
              "id": "83405d81-b933-3e5e-8590-b29d1042de24",
              "name": "\"Potential SQL Injection Due to User-Controlled Input in Raw SQL Query\"",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe vulnerability \"Potential SQL Injection Due to User-Controlled Input in Raw SQL Query\" arises when an application uses user-controlled data in a SQL query without properly sanitizing it. This can allow an attacker to manipulate the query, leading to unauthorized data access, data corruption, or even data loss.\n\nIn the provided JavaScript code, the `query` variable is passed directly into the `db.sequelize.query()` function. If the `query` variable contains user-controlled data, this could lead to a SQL Injection vulnerability.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, you should avoid using raw SQL queries whenever possible. Instead, use parameterized queries or prepared statements provided by your database library. These methods ensure that user-controlled data is properly sanitized before it's included in a SQL query.\n\nIf you must use raw SQL queries, be sure to properly sanitize user-controlled data before including it in a query. This can be done using a library that provides functions for escaping special characters in SQL queries.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere's how you might modify the provided code to use a parameterized query:\n\n```javascript\nlet userId = /* user-controlled data */;\ndb.sequelize.query(\"SELECT * FROM Users WHERE id = :userId\", {\n    replacements: { userId: userId },\n    model: db.User\n}).then(user => {\n    // ...\n});\n```\n\nIn this example, `:userId` is a placeholder that Sequelize will replace with the value of `userId` after properly sanitizing it.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe provided code requires the following library dependencies:\n\n- Sequelize: A promise-based Node.js ORM for Postgres, MySQL, MariaDB, SQLite and Microsoft SQL Server.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP SQL Injection Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/SQL_Injection_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-89: Improper Neutralization of Special Elements used in an SQL Command ('SQL Injection')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/89.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-89",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/89.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-89"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "847db4e4-f722-3d7f-bdfb-23e1e52e4e98",
              "name": "Persistent Cookies Expiration Date Not Set in Default Session Middleware Settings",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nIn JavaScript programming, particularly when using the Express.js framework, the \"Persistent Cookies Expiration Date Not Set in Default Session Middleware Settings\" vulnerability occurs when the session middleware settings do not specify an expiration date for persistent cookies. This can lead to potential security risks as the cookies can be used for an indefinite period, potentially allowing unauthorized access to sensitive information.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, it is recommended to set an expiration date for the session cookies. This can be done by adding the `maxAge` property to the `cookie` object in the session middleware settings. The `maxAge` property specifies the number of milliseconds for which the cookie will be valid.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is how you can fix the vulnerability in the provided code:\n\n```javascript\nvar session = require('express-session');\n\napp.use(session({\n  secret: 'keyboard cat',\n  resave: true,\n  saveUninitialized: true,\n  cookie: { \n    secure: false,\n    maxAge: 60000 // Set cookie expiration to 1 minute\n  }\n}));\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following library dependencies:\n\n- express\n- express-session\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Session Management Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Session_Management_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-613: Insufficient Session Expiration](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/613.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-522",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/522.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-522"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "88d6ec8d-4c6d-3b77-8542-8bca54fcdf26",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "Vulnerability: CVE-2020-11023\\nComponent: CVE-2020-11023/pkg:npm/jquery@3.2.1"
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "Potential XSS vulnerability in jQuery"
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "Update to version 3.5.0."
