            {
              "id": "8b7015f8-770c-358e-bba0-24263e0a559c",
              "name": "\"XXE Processing Vulnerabilities in User-Controlled Data in XML Parsers\"",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nXXE (XML External Entity) Processing Vulnerabilities in User-Controlled Data in XML Parsers is a type of vulnerability that occurs when an application processing XML input allows the injection of external entities. This can lead to the disclosure of internal files, denial of service, server side request forgery, port scanning from the perspective of the machine where the parser is located, and other system impacts.\n\nIn the provided JavaScript code, the application is parsing XML input from a user-controlled source (`req.files.products.data.toString('utf8')`) with the `noent` option set to `true`. This means that the parser will expand entities, which can lead to XXE vulnerabilities if the XML input includes malicious entity definitions.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate XXE vulnerabilities, you should:\n\n- Disable the use of external entities in XML parsers, which can be done in libxmljs by setting the `noent` option to `false`.\n- Use less complex data formats such as JSON, avoiding serialization of sensitive data.\n- Patch or upgrade all XML processors and libraries in use by the application or on the underlying operating system.\n- Use XML Schema Definition to validate input.\n- Verify XML or XSL file upload functionality against XEE and/or XXE attacks.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is a fixed version of the provided code:\n\n```javascript\nvar products = libxmljs.parseXmlString(req.files.products.data.toString('utf8'), {noent:false,noblanks:true})\n```\n\nIn this version, the `noent` option is set to `false`, which disables the expansion of entities and mitigates the XXE vulnerability.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe provided code requires the following library:\n\n- libxmljs\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP XXE Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/XML_External_Entity_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-611: Improper Restriction of XML External Entity Reference ('XXE')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/611.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-611",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/611.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-611"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "8d0dc7b0-9014-3517-ac7c-42708d488023",
              "name": "Unselected Field Database Query Vulnerability",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\n\"Unselected Field Database Query Vulnerability\" in JavaScript is a type of security vulnerability that occurs when a developer does not explicitly specify the fields to be returned from a database query. This can lead to the exposure of sensitive data if the query returns more data than intended. In the provided code, the `findAll` method is used without specifying the fields to be returned, which means all fields in the `Product` table will be returned.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, developers should always explicitly specify the fields to be returned from a database query. This can be done using the `attributes` option in the `findAll` method. By doing this, developers can ensure that only the necessary data is returned, reducing the risk of exposing sensitive data.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is a fixed version of the provided code:\n\n```javascript\ndb.Product.findAll({\n    attributes: ['id', 'name', 'price'], // specify the fields to be returned\n    where: {\n        name: {\n            [Op.like]: '%' + req.body.name + '%'\n        }\n    }\n}).then(products => {\n    // ...\n});\n```\n\nIn this fixed version, the `findAll` method will only return the `id`, `name`, and `price` fields from the `Product` table.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe provided code requires the following library dependencies:\n\n- Sequelize: A promise-based Node.js ORM for Postgres, MySQL, MariaDB, SQLite, and Microsoft SQL Server.\n- Express: A fast, unopinionated, and flexible Node.js web application framework.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Top Ten](https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/)\n- [CWE-209: Information Exposure Through an Error Message](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/209.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-200",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/200.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-200"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "8f1365e0-31b8-3447-b7d4-718e46049e64",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "Vulnerability: CVE-2019-11358\\nComponent: CVE-2019-11358/pkg:npm/jquery@3.2.1"
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "XSS in jQuery as used in Drupal, Backdrop CMS, and other products"
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "Update to version 3.4.0 to resolve CVE-2019-11358 or update to version 3.5.0 to resolve additional vulnerabilities for this package."
              },
              "properties": {
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security"
