            {
              "id": "98a40837-bc37-3b75-a673-964885eb949c",
              "name": "Unverified User ID Vulnerability for Authorization Checks",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe \"Unverified User ID Vulnerability for Authorization Checks\" is a security vulnerability that occurs when a web application does not properly verify the identity of a user before performing an action on their behalf. In the provided JavaScript code, the application is fetching a user from a database based on an ID provided in the request body. If an attacker can manipulate the ID in the request body, they can potentially access or modify data of other users.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, the application should implement proper authorization checks to ensure that the user is allowed to perform the requested action. This typically involves checking the user's session or token to verify their identity and permissions.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is a simple fix for the provided code, assuming that the user's ID is stored in their session:\n\n```javascript\nif (req.session.userId === req.body.id) {\n    db.User.find({\n        where: {\n            'id': req.body.id\n        }\t\t\n    }).then(user => {\n        // ...\n    });\n} else {\n    // Handle unauthorized request\n}\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe provided code appears to use the following libraries:\n\n- Express.js for handling HTTP requests and responses.\n- Sequelize for interacting with the database.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Top 10 - A5:2017-Broken Access Control](https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/2017/A5_2017-Broken_Access_Control)\n- [CWE-285: Improper Authorization](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/285.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-639",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/639.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
