            {
              "id": "9d9c1240-eb9b-35fe-9ed3-d8eed633fa39",
              "name": "Unset Domain in Default Session Middleware Settings Vulnerability",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe \"Unset Domain in Default Session Middleware Settings Vulnerability\" in JavaScript is a security flaw that occurs when the domain attribute in the session cookie is not set. This can lead to session cookies being sent to all subdomains, which can potentially expose sensitive session data to malicious subdomains.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, it is recommended to always set the domain attribute in the session cookie. This ensures that the session cookie is only sent to the specified domain and not to all subdomains.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is how you can fix the vulnerability in the provided code:\n\n```javascript\nvar express = require('express');\nvar session = require('express-session');\nvar cookieParser = require('cookie-parser');\n\nvar app = express();\n\napp.use(cookieParser());\napp.use(session({\n  secret: 'keyboard cat',\n  resave: true,\n  saveUninitialized: true,\n  cookie: { \n    secure: false,\n    domain: 'yourdomain.com' // Set your domain here\n  }\n}));\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following library dependencies:\n\n- express\n- express-session\n- cookie-parser\n\nYou can install these dependencies using npm:\n\n```bash\nnpm install express express-session cookie-parser\n```\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Session Management Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Session_Management_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-539: Information Exposure Through Persistent Cookies](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/539.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-522",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/522.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-522"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "9ddac073-078f-3f4f-be28-cec815d2e54b",
              "name": "\"EJS Output Unescaped XSS Vulnerability Detected\"",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\n\"EJS Output Unescaped XSS Vulnerability Detected\" is a Cross-Site Scripting (XSS) vulnerability that occurs when user input is outputted directly into the HTML without proper sanitization or encoding. This allows an attacker to inject malicious scripts into the web page, which can lead to various attacks such as stealing sensitive information, session hijacking, defacement of the website, etc.\n\nIn the given code snippet, the EJS template engine is used to output the product name directly into the HTML. If the product name contains any malicious scripts, they will be executed when the page is loaded.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, always sanitize and/or encode user input before outputting it into the HTML. This can be done using various methods such as HTML encoding, JavaScript encoding, CSS encoding, URL encoding, etc. depending on the context.\n\nIn the context of EJS, use `<%= %>` instead of `<%- %>` to output the data. The `<%= %>` syntax automatically HTML-encodes the output, which prevents XSS attacks.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is the fixed code:\n\n```javascript\n<td><%= output.products[i].name %></td>\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following library dependencies:\n\n- Express.js\n- EJS\n\n## OWASP Resources\n\n- [OWASP XSS Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Cross_Site_Scripting_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n\n## Common Weakness Enumeration (CWE)\n\n- [CWE-79: Improper Neutralization of Input During Web Page Generation ('Cross-site Scripting')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-79",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-79"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "a4e17d51-43bf-3f5e-8dc7-8cd4e9209183",
              "name": "\"User-Controlled Input Redirect Vulnerability\"",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nUser-Controlled Input Redirect Vulnerability, also known as Unvalidated Redirects and Forwards, is a type of vulnerability that occurs when an application uses untrusted data to determine the destination of redirects and forwards. In JavaScript, this vulnerability can occur when the application uses user-controlled input to determine the destination of the `res.redirect()` function. This can allow an attacker to redirect users to malicious websites, leading to phishing attacks, session theft, and other malicious activities.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, it is recommended to avoid using user-controlled input to determine the destination of redirects. If this is not possible, ensure that the input is properly validated and sanitized before use. This can be done by maintaining a whitelist of allowed URLs for redirection, and only allowing redirection to these URLs.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is a simple fix for the specific vulnerability sink:\n\n```javascript\nvar allowedUrls = ['http://example.com', 'http://anotherexample.com'];\n\nif (allowedUrls.indexOf(req.query.url) > -1) {\n    res.redirect(req.query.url);\n} else {\n    res.redirect('/default');\n}\n```\n\nIn this code, we maintain a whitelist of allowed URLs for redirection in the `allowedUrls` array. We then check if the user-controlled input is in this array before redirecting. If it is not, we redirect to a default URL.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the Express.js library to execute properly.\n\n## OWASP and CWE Resources\n\n- [OWASP Unvalidated Redirects and Forwards Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Unvalidated_Redirects_and_Forwards_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-601: URL Redirection to Untrusted Site ('Open Redirect')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/601.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-601",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/601.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-601"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "a7c0102e-bb5c-38ad-94d0-e0ae27ec572c",
              "name": "EJS Output Unescaped XSS Vulnerability Detected",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\n\"EJS Output Unescaped XSS Vulnerability Detected\" is a Cross-Site Scripting (XSS) vulnerability that occurs when user input is outputted directly into the webpage without being properly escaped or sanitized. This allows an attacker to inject malicious scripts into the webpage, which are then executed by the browser. In the context of EJS (Embedded JavaScript) templates, this vulnerability can occur when the `<%-` syntax is used to output unescaped data.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, always escape user input that is outputted into the webpage. This can be done using the `<%= ... %>` syntax in EJS, which automatically escapes the output. Additionally, consider using a Content Security Policy (CSP) to restrict the sources from which scripts can be loaded.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nChange the line:\n\n```javascript\nListing products with <strong>search query: </strong> <%- output.searchTerm %>\n```\n\nto:\n\n```javascript\nListing products with <strong>search query: </strong> <%= output.searchTerm %>\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following library dependencies:\n\n- EJS\n\n## OWASP and CWE Links\n\n- [OWASP Cross-Site Scripting (XSS)](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/xss/)\n- [CWE-79: Improper Neutralization of Input During Web Page Generation ('Cross-site Scripting')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html)"
