              "id": "b3887378-67c6-3dc5-96db-c29c32eca81b",
              "name": "\"XXE Vulnerability Found in libxmljs Configured with noent:true\"",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe XXE (XML External Entity) vulnerability in libxmljs configured with `noent:true` is a security flaw in JavaScript programming language that allows an attacker to exploit the XML parser. When the `noent` option is set to `true`, it allows the XML parser to substitute entities with their values. This can lead to various types of attacks such as disclosure of confidential data, denial of service, server side request forgery, port scanning from the perspective of the machine where the parser is located, and other system impacts.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, you should disable the XML external entity and DTD processing in your XML parser, as they are almost never needed for typical server-side application functionality.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nYou should set the `noent` option to `false` in the `parseXmlString` function:\n\n```javascript\nvar products = libxmljs.parseXmlString(req.files.products.data.toString('utf8'), {noent:false,noblanks:true})\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following library dependencies:\n\n- `libxmljs`: A library for parsing XML in JavaScript.\n- `req.files`: This is not a library, but a property of the `req` object in Express.js, which is populated by middleware that handles `multipart/form-data`, such as `multer`.\n\n## OWASP and CWE Resources\n\n- [OWASP XXE Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/XML_External_Entity_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-611: Improper Restriction of XML External Entity Reference ('XXE')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/611.html)"
              },
