              "id": "e98f11bd-d469-3d24-aa10-8a0ffc00adb0",
              "name": "EJS Output Unescaped Vulnerability Detected: Potential for XSS Attacks",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\n\"EJS Output Unescaped Vulnerability Detected: Potential for XSS Attacks\" is a vulnerability in JavaScript programming language that occurs when unescaped output is used in EJS templates. This can potentially lead to Cross-Site Scripting (XSS) attacks. XSS is a type of injection, in which malicious scripts are injected into otherwise benign and trusted websites. XSS attacks occur when an attacker uses a web application to send malicious code, generally in the form of a browser side script, to a different end user.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, always escape output that is dynamically included in HTML. This can be done by using the `<%= %>` syntax instead of `<%- %>` in EJS templates. The `<%= %>` syntax automatically escapes any HTML special characters in the output, preventing any injected scripts from being executed.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is how you can fix the specific vulnerability sink:\n\n```javascript\n<td><%= output.products[i].id %></td>\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following library dependencies to execute properly:\n\n- Express.js\n- EJS\n\n## OWASP Resources\n\n- [OWASP Cross-Site Scripting (XSS)](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/xss/)\n- [OWASP XSS (Cross Site Scripting) Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Cross_Site_Scripting_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n\n## Common Weakness Enumeration (CWE)\n\n- [CWE-79: Improper Neutralization of Input During Web Page Generation ('Cross-site Scripting')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
